tweet_raw: Alright after some troubleshooting I got Lutris to run one of my games under ULWGL. Bit hacky but:1.) Clone the latest ULWGL into $HOME/.local/share/ULWGL.2.) Create a script in the root of your gog game folder. I.E. if the game is Ys the script should be in $YOURLUTRISDIR/Games/gog/Ys3.) If you installed the gog game through lutris your exe will be located in drive_c/GOG Games/Your Game/some.exe. Your default prefix is the directory youve placed your script in. In your script enter in:WINEPREFIX=/path/to/game/folder GAMEID=some_id PROTONPATH=$HOME/.steam/steam/compatibilitytools.d/GE-Proton8-30 $HOME/.local/share/ULWGL/gamelauncher.sh /path/to/game/exe game_args4.) Make the file executable: sudo chmod u+x your_script.sh5.) Go into Lutris enter the configuration window for the game and change the runner to Linux.  Once the runner has changed go to game options and set the executable to your_script.sh.6.) Profit. If everything was done properly you should now be running your gog game through ULWGL ( proton without needing steam ). Apparently the game launcher script is being rewritten to python. Thinking of potentially maintaining a Rust version of the launcher script so I can add:1.) JSON configs for games so the prefix id protonpath exe path etc can just be stored somewhere and read back.2.) Automatic setting  of the WINEPREFIX to the directory the game executable is located in if the user doesnt specify the prefix. Id also like to automatically set the PROTONPATH to the latest installed version if the user fails to specify the path.

And they can use the high cost of ASICS to justify a high mint price.With that in mind here are some things I am watching out for:âš ï¸THE TEAMIs the team known? Are they doxxed?If the team is known whats their history? Have they been in the space long? Have they run other projects? How did those projects turn out? Personally I am staying away from any unknown team.  And any questionable answers to these means I am not minting and will sit tight at least until rewards are distributed .âš ï¸LEGALRunning this type of operation is complicated from a legal standpoint.  Are lawyers involved in making sure the project is saying things and doing things that would be inside the law?  Are they paying income taxes and capital gains taxes?Taking these steps shows the project is serious.  It also protects your investment since they might not intend to rug but if they are shut down by regulators you wont get your money back.Dont just take their word for it either.  Ask for proof that they are consulting legal entities that have expertise in the crypto space.âš ï¸LANGUAGECrypto mining is a long-term play.  Watch out for questionable language from the project founders themselves (holders gonna do what they do).  Some things I am watching for:- Moonboy talk and promise of massive gains- Framing other mining NFTs as competition- Promising their investment will be the bestIf they are confident in what they are building founders will not need to speak this way.
